svg.title: dna
svg.text: The sequences of all the different strands are compared to each other to find overlaps, since there are many copies of the same DNA.
These overlaps are used to stitch sequences together, so the original, unbroken DNA sequence can be read. This process is called sequence alignment.

DNA describes many aspects of what defines an organism, so when you read the DNA of two different things, it allows you to compare them in many ways as once, and in ways that would otherwise be difficult to tell.
A sample of DNA can be compared to known sequences of DNA to establish the sample’s type, for example to determine if a patient’s DNA is similar to the DNA of a person with a genetic disease.

DNA from many members of a population can be compared to determine how similar members are to each other, i.e. how diverse the population is. Populations with high diversity are more resilient, so diversity can be used to determine whichpopulations are susceptible to threats.

DNA from different organisms can be used to estimate evolutionary relationships, by turning the similarity between any two samples into ameasure of distance, so that samples which are close together are thought to be close relations.
